The paper proposes a deep reinforcement learning algorithm for continuous policies with compatible function approximation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) as it deals with learning algorithms. Additionally, the paper proposes a temporal-difference based method for learning the gradient of the value-function, which is a common technique used in reinforcement learning (cs.AI). The paper also evaluates the proposed algorithm on a challenging reinforcement learning benchmark, the octopus arm, which falls under the sub-category of Robotics (cs.RO). The use of neural networks in the proposed algorithm suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE). Finally, the paper proposes a deviator-actor-critic (DAC) model, which is a type of control system, indicating that the paper may also belong to the sub-category of Systems and Control (cs.SY).
